{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_calhoun_ver01/data/sn83016244/00513689925/1958043001/0657.xml":{"full_text":"Variety Show\nTo Have Top\nNavy Talent\nPlans tor the \"Spring Variety\nShow\" to be held in the audi\ntorium of Memorial Junior High\nSchool on Friday, May 2, at 8\np. m. are drawing to completion.\nIn addition to the many other\nnumber* there will be two male\nvocal ensembles, \"The Originals,\u201d\na quintet, features Mike Shaw,\nleader; Dave Baker tenor; Book\ner T. Washington, bass; Bernard\nWilliams, second tenor; and Hai\nley Baker, baritone.\nThese men from the USS Gil\nmore started singing together ov\ner a year ago while the ship was\ntraining in the Virgin Islands.\nThis Navy quintet has sung at\nvarious affairs and has been en\nthusaisstically received all over\nthe city.\nMike Ward, singer and guitar\nplayer, and Harold Dionne, drum\nmer from Key West High School\nlend their talent to the show.\nThis Variety Show is a school\nproject and the public is invited.\nHe Couldn\u2019t Take li\nLONDON, Ky. (AP) When\nthe Indian threw the heroic cow\nboy to the ground, 11-year-o!d\nLery Young reached for his BB\ngun and fired.\nThe whole show disappeared\nfrom the television set amid a\ntinkle of broken glass.\nLeroy got a spanking; his fa\nther an unexpected repair bill.\nt: o b o\nPHARMACY\nurner of llemintl\nmnl I. ri mu ll Streeti\nFree Delivery\nCY 6-8575\nSHOE\nSALE\nValues to $6^95\nPairs I\nDRESS\nSHOES\nFLATS!\n'EM\nTHEY\ngO^ LAST!\na^TF7 509\nB CtFTTW Duvol St.\nIQ9DQO3D9 MHMMBMnnnnnMBi\nTOP TALENT\u2014\"The Originals/' quintet from the USS Howard W. Gilmore, will bo featured In the\nvariety show to be presented at Memorial Junior High School Friday night. Loft to right, Hailey\nBaker, Dave Baker, Mike Shaw, Bernard Williams and Booker T. Washington.\u2014Citiaon Staff Photo,\nDon Pinder.\nKey Club Conducts Activity\nAt Kiwanis Inter-Club Meet\nOfficers of Key West High\nSchool\u2019s Kiwanis sponsored Key\nClub took over Tuesday night\nKiwanis Club meeting in a spe\ncial \"inter club\" session be\ntween the senior and junior\ngroups.\nOtto Busot, retiring Key Club\npresident, conducted the Kiwanis\nsession at Logun\u2019s restaurant,\nwith vocalist Diane Small and\nMary Barros at the piano giv\ning a condensed musical program\nbefore hurrying off to appear in\nthe high school Conchette show.\nFrank Motto, Key Club vice\npresident- elect, reported on the\nrecent Key Chib workshop at Or-\n.lando, Fl*., and Richard Padron,\nI president elect, briefed Kiwan\nians on the Key Club\u2019s activities\nfor the past yyear.\nOther Key Cluu officers includ\ned Jack Holcomb, new treasurer;\nBenny Trevor, secretary-elect;\nRichard Felton, retiring treasur\ner; Tommy Knowles, retiring vice\npresident; David Porch, retiring\ncorresponding secretary' and\nJoseph W. Curry, parliamentar\nian. Ira Thompson, the Key\nClub\u2019s retiring secretary, missed\nTuesday'* dinner and program.\nThe Key Clubbers invited Ki\nwanians and their wivea and dates\nto a Key Club Keyettes ban\nquet and dance May 23.\nKiwanian Art Valladares re\nported that a special Kiwanis\nChib \"fun night\" has been stated\nfor May 15 at the home of Ralph\nFaraldo. Faraldo told of plans for\nads in the Kiwanis Klatter, the\nclub\u2019s weekly news sheet, and\nHarry Jordan reported on the re\ncent Kiwanis district conference.\nMany Korean words end in \"gi,\"\nan example being that \"keilunj\nbegi\u201d is the Korean word for\nwhat we term in the United States\nas \u201clasy bones.\u201d\nI I MAR-ED'S May Day\n^9032^8\nBBIG DAYS\nDRASTIC REDUCTIONS ON NATIONALLY\nADVERTISED LADIES APPAREL\n\nTruitt ONI RACK-\nLadies and Misses all PRICE ranges\nf IAnT a. PEDAL beach\nSKORTS PUSHERS j A(KET j\nREDUCED CIQQ\nT A I/ 7 PRICED\n$2\" I REDUCED $299\nONE RACK LADIES BETTER f'b Ofl\nDRESSES 8\"\nWIDE SELECTION OF STYLES and FABRICS\n3 GROUPS 2-PIECE 3 GROUPS\nMatching SKIRT and BLOUSE\nDRESSES BLOUSES\n8899 $699 99c $199\nand $1099 and $2.99\nMAR-EDS DUVAL ST.\nMsgr. Concannon\nDies On Altar\nBEVERLY HILLS, Calif, (JR\nThe pastor of the Catholic church\nwhere many film stars worship\ndied on the altar while ceiobiating\nMass.\n\u201cSjlost Sacred Heart of Jesus,\nhave mercy on us,\u201d intoned the\nRt. Rev. Ms\u00abr. Patrick J. Con\ncannon, 63. at the conclusion of\nthe service yesterday. Then he\ncollapsed on the carpeted stairs of\nthe altar at Good Shepherd\nChurch.\nAnother priest, the Rev. Felix\nDoherty, administered the last\nrites of the church as the Ireland\nborn monsignor lay on the altar.\nPoverty Reported\nST. LOUIS \u00dcB\u2014The Rev. Dr. Al\nford Carleton told the Congrega\ntional Christian Conference of Mis\nsouri last night that the Christian\nchurch in Asia and Africa has\n\"been operating at a level of pov\nerty not worthy of us.\"\nDr. Carleton recently returned\nfrom a tour of Asia and Africa.\nThe Congregational Christian\nchurches plan to raise 7W million\ndollars in the next two years for\nhigher education overseas and in\nthis country.\nSome Degree\nOf Recovery\nSeen In \u20195B\nWASHINGTON (R\u2014A baker-eco\nnomist said today the recession\nshould hit bottom soon with some\ndegree of recovery thia year.\nThe decline is moderating, said\nAlan H. Temple, executive vice\npresident of the First Na Zonal\nCity Bank of New York, but state\nment* that it ha* already touched\nbottom \"must still be based on\n'faith rather than on demonstrated\nfact.\"\nTemple's estimates, prepared\nfor the annual meeting of the U.S.\nChamber of Commerce, were les*\noptimistic than some from admin\nistration spokesmen.\nSecretary of Commerce Weeks\n10 days ago said he believed the\nbottom already has been reached\nand the recovery will come by\nlate summer. President Eisenhow\ner last week said the recession\nhas been \"flattening out for some\ntime.\"\nTemple said he could agree that\n\"the foundation for bottoming out\nis developing,' and it cannot be\nlong delayed.\u201d He went on: \"Safe\nguards against a downward spiral\nof the intensity of the great de\npression are numerous and strong.\n\"Therefore our greatest concern\nin this business decline is not its\ndepth, which should not be grave\nly below present levels, but the\ntime required to resume general\ngrowth and to reattain the pros\nperity of which thia country ia\ncapable.\"\nAnother speaker, Rep. Richard\nM. Simpson (R-Pa), a member of\nthe House Ways and Means Com\nmittee, said that huge Federal\nspending programs, a* an anti\nrecession cure, would be folly, but\nhe declared in favor of tax reduc\ntion.\nTraffic Toll Off\nCHICAGO (JR The nation's\ntraffic death ton for the first\nquarter of thia year was 7,730, a\ndecrease of I per cent compared\nto 1,250 in the first throe months\nin 1857.\nThe National Safety Council\nsaid the 2,630 traffic death* in\nMarch wa* nine per cent lower\nthan in March laat year and the\nlowest for March aince 1955.\nTwenty-nine states reported a\ndecrease in deaths in the first\nthree month* this year compared\nto the first quarter of 1957, 17 had\nincrease* and one reported no\nchange.\n^\\MAMMOTH\nLMfr/ 5 large I\nAssortment I\nLAMPS\nv X w\nFro m\nBUNK BED 998\nwith Innerspring Mattress H\nSi MSB I\n9x12 SET OF 3 I\nA LINOLEUM slft9Bl\nRUGS s4s?^ JSWT .bu.\nMAY I\nBUTTERFLY I\nCHAIR I\nCOVERS X^^f?\nJ Carriages I\n$398 K Boodle Buggies 5\n1 sl4\u2019B X 3\n-3\nHMM HMMI\n(Tremendous p A ir\n(SAVINGS CR/B Crib 1\nImS Ma,,resseJ\nI ATurn I EACH I\nIjTEMsP 9 B L*?\u2019 8\nFLEMING STREET\nFURNITURE CO.\n909 FLEMING STREET PHONE CY 6-6031\nWednesday, April N, mi KEY WIST CfTtZIN\nPage 5","height":"29102","width":"20725"}}
